    slug: 'like-nouns-slipping-into-verbs',
    category: 'Exhibition',
    content: `<p>During his decade-long career as an anthropologist, Richard Nonas conducted fieldwork among several Native American tribes, including the Tohono Oʼodham of Mexico. From them, he encountered a cultural framework for understanding space through "markers," objects whose meanings shift according to physical context and the individual engaging with them.</p><p>Nonas often invoked the analogy of a cactus in the desert. For one person, it might hold a private memory; for another, it serves as a landmark or navigational device; for others, it carries a folktale and becomes part of collective memory. The potency of his sculptures lies in this ambiguity and rejection of fixed semantics. Their meanings remain malleable, in flux.</p><p>His sculptures, primarily minimal rectangular and linear forms in metal and wood, function as spatial markers themselves, like the cactus. Paired with a space, they prompt impressions and memories. Central to his practice is the transformation of space into place. Alongside place-making, Nonas embraced ambiguity and liminality, emphasizing tensions between space and place, recognizable and abstract form, physical and imagined space, memory and reality.</p><p>The works exhibited at Bangkok Kunsthalle fall into two categories: linear and rectangular forms. The linear constructions demarcate the borders of imagined places, exemplified by "Boundary Man" (1974). Composed of two perpendicular steel lines, 17 and 14 meters long, the work intersects two rooms, extending through partitions to delineate boundaries of a place that cannot physically exist. Its scale denies a singular viewpoint; viewers must move through space and rely on memory to complete the scene, generating ambiguity between past and present, reality and recollection.</p><p>Complementing these are low-lying rectangular steel forms that act as monuments within an imagined landscape. Their abstract geometry may recall a childhood floorplan, Mesoamerican platforms, or an altar. The exhibition space shifts between nostalgia, archaeology, and ritual, making locality and positioning as crucial as the objects.</p><p>Housed in the abandoned Thai Watana Panich building, Bangkok Kunsthalle offers an ideal stage. Its repurposed architecture echoes the liminality of Nonas' sculpture, occupying a front lobby poised between space and place.</p><p> Artist Biography </p><p>Richard Nonas (1936 - 2021, USA) was born in New York and studied literature before turning to social anthropology. He spent a decade conducting fieldwork among American Indians, an experience that profoundly shaped his later sculptural practice and his understanding of spatial perception. In the mid-1960s, at age 30, he shifted to sculpture, developing a Minimalist vocabulary centered on the idea of place.</p><p>During the 1970s, Nonas was part of a group of artists and curators seeking alternative exhibition spaces. His works, using timbers, beams, granite curbstones, and steel planes, often rest directly on the ground. Less formal objects than spatial markers, they interrupt and activate space, revealing the interdependence of sculpture and site while generating philosophical and emotional resonance.</p>`
