    slug: 'poetics-of-horizontality',
    category: 'Exhibition',
    content: `<p>The exhibition "Poetics of Horizontality" (2025) by Nalattaphorn Nanta and Siriwan Simingam presents delicate stone grids across the third floor of Bangkok Kunsthalle. The work engages the building's material memory, visibly marked by past fires. Through subtle spatial inscription, the artists map and interpret this altered architectural environment.</p><p>Fragments of cement and debris detached from ceilings and walls are retrieved from the site and repositioned along faint scorched shadows left by boxes that once occupied the floor. The configuration follows a loose yet resonant order, evoking the grid not as control but as a poetic framework for remembrance. The artists describe the gesture as creating their own "museum," where value arises not from institutional authority but from care and attention.</p><p>The installation operates through three actions: collecting, arranging, and healing. By gathering fragments otherwise dismissed as rubble, the artists attribute value through attentive engagement, recalling archaeological processes of recovery. Arrangement is equally significant. The stones form ephemeral grids that function as archive and spatial reading, each fragment contributing to a latent order.</p><p>The work renders visible the building's palimpsestic character, layered with temporalities and traces. The grid remains irregular, marked by gaps and imperfections that resist the idea of neutral space and affirm its entanglement with history and decay. Its fragility reinforces contingency. The stones are unsecured; a gust of wind or passing cat could disrupt the composition. This precariousness underscores the transient nature of all structures, formal or informal, subject to time and transformation.</p><p>At its core, the exhibition articulates a poetics of care and a politics of attention. Healing emerges through witnessing and quiet recomposition rather than erasure. Horizontality refers to what lies parallel to the horizon, the shifting boundary where sky and earth meet. Both perceptually real and elusive, the horizon frames phenomena while remaining absent. It limits and enables.</p><p>This framework informs Bangkok Kunsthalle's broader research into material and spatial practices that attend to the ground. Within this lineage, "Poetics of Horizontality" becomes a modest yet profound act of spatial care, recalling forgotten order while opening renewal: to commemorate, and to begin again.</p><p> Artist Biography </p><p>Nalattaphorn Nanta (b. 2000, Thailand) explores the perspectives and emotional states experienced at different stages of life. Her practice examines how behavior and thought are shaped by family as the smallest yet most formative social unit. Through an evolving understanding of human emotion, she reflects on its causes and possible resolutions, seeking deeper insight into life. Her work often centers on the interplay of happiness and suffering, interpreting life's complexities while offering an uplifting and encouraging presence to viewers.</p><p>Siriwan Simingam (b. 1998, Thailand) investigates the roles, mindsets, and complex relationships of women in contemporary society. She critiques the cultural expectations and pressures that persist despite increased intellectual freedom and self-determination. Initially combining sculptural and painterly techniques with doodle-like linework, her practice has developed into a distinctive Pop-Surrealist style, creating narrative characters that embody her reflections on female experience and social dynamics.</p>`
