    slug: 'mitta-del-santi',
    category: 'Exhibition',
    content: `<p>"Mitta del Santi" (2025), a site-specific textile installation by Ploenchan Vinyaratn, responds to the history of Bangkok Kunsthalle, formerly the Thai Watana Panich publishing house. Fabric remnants are cut into circular forms echoing the printing house's logo of three interlocking circles. A total of 399 circles are imprinted with words drawn from children's educational books once produced there. Reassembled, these textual fragments are rewoven into a new narrative, transforming the memory of the site into a living story.</p><p>Here, weaving becomes a method of world-making: threads, people, and histories interlaced into forms larger than themselves. The exhibition aligns with the Kunsthalle and Khao Yai Art Forest's ethos of site-specificity, ecological awareness, and community participation.</p><p>The installation unfolds as a participatory practice. Vinyaratn deconstructs and reassembles looms to produce monumental textiles beyond conventional frameworks. Central to this process is her invitation to Thai women, many of them longtime collaborators, to join in the making. Through collective labor, weaving becomes both craft and community. Fragments of earlier works are reimagined and reassembled, allowing forms, textures, and colors to reconnect in unexpected ways. These are not remnants but continuations, materials beginning again with purpose and grace.</p><p>Often using repurposed materials such as cassette tape, fishing nylon, brass strings, and Lurex yarn, Vinyaratn creates tactile narratives of memory, ecology, and shared experience. Her works interrogate urban history, consumption, and waste, while their flat surfaces expand and adapt architecturally across floors and walls. At its core, her distinctive formal language endures.</p><p>Weaving, with warp and weft constantly shifting in relation to one another, becomes a metaphor for connection, collaboration, and care. This ethos extends to "Mitta in Practice", a hands-on workshop inviting participants to transform discarded materials into new stories.</p><p>In reconfiguring looms as ritual and architecture, Vinyaratn affirms textile's power to embody resilience, collaboration, and collective imagination.</p><p> Artist Biography </p><p>Ploenchan Vinyaratn (b. 1972, Thailand) is acclaimed for transforming fiber into a medium of environmental urgency. Long before sustainability became a global imperative, she pioneered a zero-waste practice, turning discarded materials—aluminium ribbons, plastics, fishing nets, cassette tapes—into large-scale installations that interrogate ecological fragility and humanity's troubled relationship with nature. Celebrated for her dual role as artist and environmental advocate, she received the Angela Award for Lifetime Achievement in 2024. Her works appear in major collections across Thailand and have been exhibited internationally, including Singapore, Korea, Greece, and the United States.</p>`
